    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-03-21T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-03-21T04:00:00-05:00" n="208"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d208">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114A/3–2145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-21T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 21, 1945—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:32 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1686. American Interests—Japan. Your 756, February 19.<note n="36"
                        xml:id="d208fn1">Not printed.</note> Swiss note March 16 states Gorgé will
                    forward translation regulations concerning POW camps which appear in official
                    Japanese gazette. He adds that Jap Foreign Ministry never transmits such
                    regulations protecting Power or Intercross.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[In telegram 1296, March 31, 6 p.m., the Department requested the Swiss
                        Government to inform the Japanese Government that the Japanese reply to
                        American charges of decapitation of an American airman by Japanese forces
                        was inacceptable (see telegram 731, February 1, 6 p.m., from Bern, <ref
                            target="#pg_320">page 320</ref>). In telegram 1371, April 6, the
                        Department requested the Swiss Government to protest the murder by Japanese
                        authorities of four American civilians interned at Manila. For texts of
                        telegrams 1296 and 1371, see Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                            >Bulletin</hi>, September 9, 1945, pages 351 and 352.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
